column5: {50106: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50106",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to perform a Responder poisoner SMB attack, which is a type of Adversary-in-the-Middle attack. column5: {1564: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting access to the \\\'/login.htm\\\' page on a public-facing web server, which could be an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the login page to gain initial access to the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1564", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting access to the login page, which could be an attempt to use valid credentials to gain unauthorized access to the web application or network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {10088: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10088",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the \\\'Beyond Keylogger\\\' malware, which is designed to capture user input such as keystrokes to steal sensitive information like credentials. This aligns with the \\\'Input Capture\\\' technique described in MITRE ATT&CK."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10088", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1020",\\n    "Technique name": "Automated Exfiltration",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exfiltrate data, such as sensitive documents, through the use of automated processing after being gathered during Collection\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects the exfiltration of keylogger data via SMTP, which is an automated process for sending the collected data to the attacker. column5: {29379: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29379",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1020",\\n    "Technique name": "Automated Exfiltration",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exfiltrate data, such as sensitive documents, through the use of automated processing after being gathered during Collection\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound encrypted traffic from a known Trojan dropper, which could be used for automated exfiltration of data over an encrypted channel. The rule specifically mentions \\\'potential exfiltration\\\', indicating that the detected traffic may be related to data exfiltration."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29379", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound encrypted traffic from a known Trojan dropper, which could potentially be used for exfiltrating data over the established command and control channel."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29379",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule specifically mentions that the detected traffic is encrypted, which aligns with the technique of using an encrypted channel to conceal command and control communications."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {58733: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58733",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to exploit the Log4j vulnerability in Apache web servers, which is a public-facing application. The rule looks for specific patterns in the HTTP client body that indicate an attempt to execute remote code via the Log4j vulnerability, which aligns with the technique of exploiting a public-facing application to gain initial access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58733",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Log4j vulnerability being targeted by this rule can potentially be used by adversaries to bypass security controls and execute arbitrary code on the vulnerable system. By exploiting this vulnerability, adversaries can evade defense mechanisms and gain unauthorized access or execute malicious payloads."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {24087: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24087",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (Bledoor) that tunnels TCP traffic within UDP packets, likely to evade detection or bypass network filtering rules. This aligns with the technique of Protocol Tunneling, where adversaries encapsulate one protocol within another to obfuscate their communications."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24087", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1095",\\n    "Technique name": "Non-Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an OSI non-application layer protocol for communication between host and C2 server or among infected hosts within a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for UDP traffic (a non-application layer protocol) being used for command and control communication between the infected host and an external server. This matches the technique of using non-application layer protocols for C2 communications."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {7551: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "7551",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1115",\\n    "Technique name": "Clipboard Data",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may collect data stored in the clipboard from users copying information within or between applications"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the Ardamax keylogger, which is a type of malware that captures user input data, including clipboard data. column5: {25579: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "25579",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1566",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a phishing attack where a malicious file named \\\'BookingInfo.zip\\\' is delivered via an HTTP response, likely as part of a phishing campaign. column5: {60338: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60338",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Server Software Component\\\', \\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound connections from a compromised web server running a malicious PHP web shell named DiveShell, which is likely abusing legitimate server software components to establish persistent access and execute commands on the system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60338", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Command and Scripting Interpreter\\\', \\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for specific content related to executing commands via the DiveShell web shell, which leverages command and scripting interpreters on the compromised server to run malicious code."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {49540: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49540",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1098",\\n    "Technique name": "Account Manipulation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may manipulate accounts to maintain and/or elevate access to victim systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to change the WordPress user roles configuration, specifically trying to grant the \\\'administrator\\\' role, which could allow an adversary to manipulate accounts and gain elevated privileges on the system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49540", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "By attempting to grant the \\\'administrator\\\' role, an adversary could potentially abuse the credentials of an existing account to gain elevated privileges and maintain access to the system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {31978: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31978",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in a public-facing web application (CGI environment variable injection) by an external source, which aligns with the T1190 technique of exploiting public-facing applications to gain initial access to a network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31978", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for an attempt to inject malicious code into a CGI environment variable, which could potentially be used to bypass security controls and execute arbitrary commands on the server, aligning with the T1211 technique of exploiting vulnerabilities for defense evasion."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {37313: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37313",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exfiltrate data over the SMTP protocol, which is an alternative protocol to the typical command and control channel used by adversaries. The rule looks for specific patterns in the SMTP traffic that indicate an attempt to exfiltrate data using external entity references."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37313",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1030",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Transfer Size Limits",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'An adversary may exfiltrate data in fixed size chunks instead of whole files or limit packet sizes below certain thresholds\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "While not explicitly mentioned in the rule, the use of external entity references could be a way for an adversary to split and exfiltrate data in smaller chunks, potentially to evade detection or bypass data transfer size limits imposed by security controls."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {61160: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "61160",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Server Software Component\\\', \\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound connections from a compromised system running a JSP web shell named \\\'JSP2Shell\\\', which is a type of malicious server software component that allows adversaries to gain persistent access and control over the server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "61160", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Application Layer Protocol\\\', \\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for HTTP traffic, which is an application layer protocol, indicating that the adversary may be using this protocol to communicate with the compromised system and blend in with normal web traffic to avoid detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {39930: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "39930",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1552",\\n    "Technique name": "Unsecured Credentials",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to disclose credentials from a Siemens IP camera by accessing the \\\'readfile.cgi\\\' script with the \\\'ADMINID\\\' parameter, which suggests an attempt to retrieve unsecured or improperly stored administrator credentials."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "39930", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for an attempt to retrieve administrator credentials (\\\'ADMINID\\\'), which could potentially be used by an adversary to gain unauthorized access or escalate privileges using a valid account."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {49789: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49789",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP traffic from an infected host to an external IP, which could be an indication of command and control communication using the application layer protocol HTTP. column5: {59051: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59051",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to upload a PHP webshell named \\\'Andela\\\', which is a capability that can be used by adversaries to gain remote access and execute commands on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59051", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic from an external network to an internal HTTP port, which could indicate an attempt to exploit a public-facing web application to gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {20618: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "20618",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1552",\\n    "Technique name": "Unsecured Credentials",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to disclose database credentials for the Sage SalesLogix application, which suggests that the adversary is trying to find and obtain unsecured or improperly stored credentials on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "20618", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"],\\n    "Explanation": "By attempting to disclose database credentials, the adversary is likely trying to obtain valid account credentials, which could be used for various purposes such as gaining initial access, maintaining persistence, escalating privileges, or evading defenses."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {28349: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28349",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1047",\\n    "Technique name": "Windows Management Instrumentation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to execute malicious commands and payloads\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to access the Microsoft Windows WMI administrator tools object viewer ActiveX control, which could be used by an adversary to execute malicious commands and payloads through WMI."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "28349",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that an adversary may be attempting to exploit a vulnerability in a client application (browser plugin) to gain code execution on the target system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {60451: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60451",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an inbound connection attempt to a PHP web shell named \\\'Erne\\\', which is a malicious server software component that can be used by adversaries to gain persistent access to the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60451", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect an inbound connection attempt to a web shell, which is often used by adversaries to exploit vulnerabilities in public-facing web applications and gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {37383: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37383",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to log in to a web application using the default username and password combination (\\\'username:password\\\'), which is a form of abusing valid accounts to gain unauthorized access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37383", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for attempts to exploit a public-facing web application (Digi) by using the default credentials, which could allow an adversary to gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {17265: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "17265",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1176",\\n    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse Internet browser extensions to establish persistent access to victim systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to bypass access controls in the Mozilla Firefox browser plugin, which could allow an adversary to establish persistent access by abusing a browser extension."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "17265", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the adversary is attempting to exploit a vulnerability in the Firefox browser plugin, which may require user interaction or execution to be successful."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {30510: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30510",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1600",\\n    "Technique name": "Weaken Encryption",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may compromise a network device\\\'s encryption capability in order to bypass encryption that would otherwise protect data communications\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit the OpenSSL Heartbleed vulnerability (CVE-2014-0160), which allows an attacker to read sensitive memory from a server and potentially obtain private encryption keys, effectively weakening the encryption used to protect communications."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {29615: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "29615",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound connections from the internal network to an external web service (/sizemore/css5.php?a), which could be used by a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Keylogger) to relay data from the compromised system. column5: {59023: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59023",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an outbound connection attempt from a compromised system to an external web service, which could be used by the adversary to relay data or commands. column5: {45470: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "45470",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to download a file named \\\'sm.txt\\\' from the path \\\'/kelly6666/\\\', which could be an indicator of a tool or malicious payload being transferred from an external system to the compromised host."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "45470", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic from the internal network ($HOME_NET) to the external network ($EXTERNAL_NET), which could indicate an attempt to exploit a public-facing application or service to gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {17154: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "17154",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the Mozilla Firefox browser plugin parameter array, which could allow an adversary to execute code on the client system. This aligns with the \\\'Exploitation for Client Execution\\\' technique, where adversaries exploit vulnerabilities in client applications to gain code execution."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "17154", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is triggered when a client system communicates with an external web server, suggesting that the exploitation attempt could occur through a drive-by compromise scenario, where a user\\\'s system is compromised by visiting a malicious website."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {36338: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36338",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1598",\\n    "Technique name": "Phishing for Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may send phishing messages to elicit sensitive information that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a potential phishing attempt by looking for specific indicators in an HTTP response, such as the presence of the string \\\'<!-- PHOEN!X -->\\\' and fields related to submitting a password (\\\'apass\\\' and \\\'submit.x\\\'). column5: {5780: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "5780",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a potential keylogger activity, which is a form of input capture technique used by adversaries to collect sensitive information such as credentials or other user input data."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "5780", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the detected activity involves exfiltrating captured data (potentially from a keylogger) over an SMTP channel, which could be used as a command and control channel by the adversary."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {19171: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19171",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer 8 by loading the ieshims.dll library, which could allow an adversary to execute code on the client system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19171", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic from the internal network ($HOME_NET) to an external web server ($EXTERNAL_NET), suggesting an attempt to exploit a public-facing application (in this case, Internet Explorer) to gain initial access or execute code on the internal system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50954: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50954",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to communicate with the PhpSploit backdoor, which is a malicious server software component that can be used by adversaries to gain persistent access to the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50954",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for HTTP traffic from an external network to an internal web server, which could be an indication of an adversary using a web service to communicate with a compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50467: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50467",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1003",\\n    "Technique name": "OS Credential Dumping",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to dump credentials to obtain account login and credential material, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system and software\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to use Mimikatz, a well-known credential dumping tool, over the SMB protocol. Mimikatz is commonly used by adversaries to extract credentials from the operating system, aligning with the T1003 technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50467", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1550",\\n    "Technique name": "Use Alternate Authentication Material",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use alternate authentication material, such as password hashes, Kerberos tickets, and application access tokens, in order to move laterally within an environment and bypass normal system access controls\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "Mimikatz is capable of extracting various types of authentication material, including password hashes and Kerberos tickets. By detecting its use, the rule may indicate an attempt to leverage alternate authentication material for lateral movement, as described in the T1550 technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42836: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42836",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Backdoor.Chopper web shell, which is a malicious server software component that allows adversaries to gain persistent access and control over the compromised system. column5: {22061: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "22061",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to load a malicious IFRAME, which is a technique used by the Alureon malware to leverage web services for malicious purposes, such as relaying data or hosting malicious content."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "22061", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect a drive-by compromise attempt, where the user\\\'s system is compromised by visiting a website that loads malicious content, in this case, a malicious IFRAME."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48501: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48501",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1529",\\n    "Technique name": "System Shutdown/Reboot",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may shutdown/reboot systems to interrupt access to, or aid in the destruction of, those systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a malware variant that downloads a tool capable of executing the \\\'shutdown /r /f /t 000\\\' command, which forcibly reboots the system immediately. column5: {32804: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32804",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect known malicious JavaScript packers, which are commonly used in drive-by compromise attacks. These attacks exploit vulnerabilities in web browsers or browser plugins to deliver and execute malicious code on a victim\\\'s system when they visit a compromised website."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32804", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The detection of a malicious JavaScript packer could indicate an attempt by an adversary to stage capabilities, such as delivering and executing a malicious payload, on the victim\\\'s system through a compromised website."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48508: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48508",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect outbound connections from a compromised system to an external web service, which could be used by the ZeusPanda malware for command and control purposes. The rule looks for HTTP requests to specific WordPress plugin directories, which could be an indicator of the malware attempting to communicate with its command and control infrastructure via a legitimate web service."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48508", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1001",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Obfuscation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obfuscate command and control traffic to make it more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule checks for the absence of a \\\'Referer\\\' header in the HTTP request, which could be an attempt by the malware to obfuscate its traffic and make it more difficult to detect. column5: {60297: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60297",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an inbound connection attempt to a web shell named \\\'Cybershell\\\', which is a type of malicious code that can be uploaded to a web server to gain unauthorized access. column5: {58789: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58789",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to exploit the Log4j vulnerability in Apache web servers, which are Internet-facing applications. column5: {44563: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44563",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from the internal network to the internet, which could be an indication of malware using the application layer protocol (HTTP) for command and control communication, blending in with normal web traffic to evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44563",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1219",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Access Software",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'An adversary may use legitimate desktop support and remote access software to establish an interactive command and control channel to target systems within networks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule mentions \\\'PowerShell Empire variant\\\', which is a type of remote access tool or software that can be used by adversaries for command and control purposes."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {19079: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19079",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer\\\'s getElementById object, which could lead to a drive-by compromise attack where the user\\\'s system is compromised simply by visiting a malicious website."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19079", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for an exploit that targets a vulnerability in the client-side Internet Explorer browser, which could allow an adversary to execute malicious code on the user\\\'s system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {59926: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59926",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to spawn a remote shell using Python\\\'s pty.spawn() function, which is a command and scripting interpreter technique used by adversaries to execute commands or scripts on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59926",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is triggered by traffic from an external network to an internal HTTP port, suggesting that the adversary may have exploited a public-facing application to gain initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56603: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56603",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect outbound HTTP traffic from a compromised system to an external network, which could be indicative of command and control communication using an application layer protocol (HTTP) to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56603",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific patterns in the HTTP headers and URI that could indicate the use of a legitimate web service for command and control communication or data exfiltration."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56603",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect a specific malware (Win.Backdoor.CSBundle_Original) that attempts to masquerade its communication as legitimate web traffic by using specific HTTP headers and URI patterns."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column7: {56603: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56603",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect outbound HTTP traffic from a compromised system to an external network, which could be indicative of command and control communication using an application layer protocol (HTTP) to blend in with normal web traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56603",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific patterns in the HTTP headers and URI that could indicate the use of a legitimate web service for command and control communication or data exfiltration."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56603",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect a specific malware (Win.Backdoor.CSBundle_Original) that attempts to masquerade its communication as legitimate web traffic by using specific HTTP headers and URI patterns."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50095: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50095",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1649",\\n    "Technique name": "Steal or Forge Authentication Certificates",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal or forge certificates used for authentication to access remote systems or resources\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to use a self-signed certificate, which could be an indicator of an adversary trying to forge or steal authentication certificates for malicious purposes, such as gaining unauthorized access to systems or resources."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50095", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The use of a self-signed certificate could be an attempt by an adversary to perform an Adversary-in-the-Middle (AiTM) attack, where they position themselves between the client and server to intercept and manipulate the communication."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56616: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56616",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP POST requests to specific URLs, which indicates the use of an application layer protocol (HTTP) for communication, likely for command and control purposes. column5: {44564: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP connections from the internal network to the internet, which could be an indication of malware using the application layer protocol (HTTP) for command and control communication, blending in with normal web traffic to evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1001",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Obfuscation",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may obfuscate command and control traffic to make it more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for a specific pattern in the HTTP Cookie header, which could be an obfuscation technique used by the malware to hide its command and control traffic within legitimate-looking HTTP requests."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect a variant of the PowerShell Empire malware, which is known to use masquerading techniques to disguise its network traffic as legitimate HTTP requests, in an attempt to evade detection by security tools."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42834: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42834",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a web shell connection from an external source to an internal web server, which could be used by an adversary to relay data or commands to the compromised system via a web service."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42834", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for the \\\'X-Forwarded-For\\\' header, which is commonly used by proxy servers to identify the originating IP address of a client. column5: {49455: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49455",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to upload a Perl webshell script, which is a type of malicious code that can be used to gain unauthorized access and execute commands on the server. This aligns with the \\\'Stage Capabilities\\\' technique, where adversaries set up tools or capabilities on the compromised system for further exploitation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49455", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for an attempt to upload a webshell script to a web server, which is a public-facing application. column5: {26774: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "26774",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound connections from the internal network to an external HTTP port, which could indicate an attempt to exploit a public-facing application or service to gain initial access or maintain persistence within the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "26774", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1133",\\n    "Technique name": "External Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may leverage external-facing remote services to initially access and/or persist within a network\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for outbound connections to external HTTP ports, which could be an attempt to leverage external remote services for initial access or persistence within the network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "26774",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for a specific URI (/loader.cpl) and HTTP header pattern that could be an attempt by the malware to masquerade as legitimate traffic to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {49450: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49450",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to upload a CFM webshell, which is a type of malicious server software component that can be used by adversaries to gain persistent access to the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "49450", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The CFM webshell being uploaded is a capability that can be used by the adversary during the targeting phase of an attack to execute further malicious activities on the compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {14074: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "14074",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the SpyBoss Pro keylogger, which is designed to capture user input data such as keystrokes. This aligns with the Input Capture technique (T1056) described in the MITRE ATT&CK framework."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "14074", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects the SpyBoss Pro keylogger attempting to exfiltrate captured data (log files) over SMTP, which is a common command and control channel used by malware. This matches the Exfiltration Over C2 Channel technique (T1041) in MITRE ATT&CK."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56615: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56615",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from the internal network to the internet, which could be an attempt by the Cobalt Strike beacon to communicate with its command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP. This technique allows the malware to blend in with legitimate traffic and evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56615",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific patterns in the HTTP request that could be used by the Cobalt Strike beacon to masquerade as legitimate traffic, such as requests for advertisements, assets, or preferences. This technique helps the malware evade detection by appearing benign."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {16573: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16573",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects obfuscated ActiveX object instantiation via the unescape function, which is a technique used to obfuscate and execute malicious code. This aligns with the T1027 technique where adversaries obfuscate files or information to evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16573", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for attempts to instantiate an ActiveX object, which could potentially be used to exploit vulnerabilities in client applications like web browsers to execute malicious code. column5: {59929: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to download a JSP webshell named \\\'Behinder\\\', which is a malicious server software component that can be used by adversaries to establish persistent access on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59929", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Behinder webshell detected by the Snort rule can be used by adversaries to stage additional capabilities, such as uploading and executing malicious payloads, on the compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57908: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57908",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the Microsoft Exchange autodiscover feature, which is a public-facing application, by sending a malicious request that could potentially lead to server-side request forgery."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57908", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1211",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in the Microsoft Exchange autodiscover feature, which could potentially allow an adversary to bypass security controls and gain unauthorized access or perform malicious actions."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {4917: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "4917",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer by obfuscating JavaScript code that triggers an onload event and prompts for user input, which could potentially lead to code execution on the client system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "4917", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions \\\'obfuscation\\\' in the message, indicating that the detected JavaScript code is obfuscated, likely to evade detection or analysis, which aligns with the Obfuscated Files or Information technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

The rule specifically looks for an outbound connection to a gate.php script, which could be used to exfiltrate captured keystrokes or other user input data. column5: {39755: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "39755",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects the use of PowerShell commands, which is a command and scripting interpreter, to execute malicious activities related to the Retefe Trojan variant."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "39755", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the Retefe Trojan variant relies on user interaction, such as visiting a malicious website, to execute its payload and install a malicious certificate."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "39755",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1649",\\n    "Technique name": "Steal or Forge Authentication Certificates",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\\"Adversaries may steal or forge certificates used for authentication to access remote systems or resources\\\\""],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule explicitly mentions the installation of a malicious certificate, which aligns with the technique of stealing or forging authentication certificates to gain unauthorized access."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47900: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47900",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP traffic from the internal network to the internet, which could be an indicator of malware using the application layer protocol HTTP to communicate with a command and control server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47900",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for a pattern in the HTTP URI (/pser?[A-F0-9]{3,84}(BBZ|BBY)) that is associated with the OilRig malware variant, which likely uses a web service for command and control communication."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38724: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38724",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects outbound GET requests from a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Renegin) that contains indicators of keylogging and clipboard data collection capabilities, which align with the Input Capture technique used by adversaries to obtain sensitive information through intercepting user input."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38724", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1115",\\n    "Technique name": "Clipboard Data",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may collect data stored in the clipboard from users copying information within or between applications"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions \\\'Clipboard-Logger Enabled\\\' in the content match, indicating that the Trojan has the capability to capture data from the clipboard, which is a technique used by adversaries to collect sensitive information."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {59354: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59354",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to upload a PHP web shell named \\\'SmallShell\\\', which is a type of malicious server software component that can be used by adversaries to gain persistent access and control over the compromised server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "59354", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule looks for specific patterns in the uploaded file data that indicate the presence of PHP code for executing system commands using functions like \\\'shell_exec\\\', which is a common technique used by web shells to run arbitrary commands on the compromised server."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {30517: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30517",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1595",\\n    "Technique name": "Active Scanning",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may execute active reconnaissance scans to gather information that can be used during targeting\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect potential attempts to exploit the OpenSSL Heartbleed vulnerability (CVE-2014-0160), which allows an attacker to read sensitive memory data from a vulnerable server. This can be considered an active scanning technique, as the attacker is actively probing the server for vulnerabilities that can be exploited."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "30517",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is specifically looking for traffic on common network service ports (e.g., 21, 25, 443, 465, 636, 992, 993, 995, 2484), which suggests that the attacker may be attempting to discover and potentially exploit vulnerabilities in network services running on the target system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {300357: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "300357",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to transfer a PHP webshell script, which is a type of malicious script that can be executed on a web server to gain unauthorized access or perform malicious actions. The rule looks for specific patterns in the file data that are indicative of a webshell script, such as the presence of the \\\'<?$\\\' PHP tag and the \\\'eval(gzuncompress(base64_decode(\\\' function, which is commonly used to decode and execute obfuscated code. This aligns with the \\\'Command and Scripting Interpreter\\\' technique, where adversaries abuse scripting languages like PHP to execute malicious commands or scripts on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "300357",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1140",\\n    "Technique name": "Deobfuscate/Decode Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use Obfuscated Files or Information to hide artifacts of an intrusion from analysis\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule specifically looks for the presence of the \\\'eval(gzuncompress(base64_decode(\\\' function, which is commonly used to decode and execute obfuscated code. This suggests that the webshell script being transferred is likely obfuscated or encoded to evade detection. The rule aims to detect this deobfuscation or decoding process, which aligns with the \\\'Deobfuscate/Decode Files or Information\\\' technique used by adversaries to hide malicious artifacts from analysis."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {7544: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n    {\\n        "sid": "7544",\\n        "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n        "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n        "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\\\'"],\\n        "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect the activity of the PerfectKeylogger malware, which is a keylogger used to capture user input data, such as keystrokes and credentials. The rule looks for a specific header (\\\'X-Mailer: CSMTPConnection\\\') in SMTP traffic, which is a known indicator of the PerfectKeylogger malware attempting to exfiltrate captured data. Therefore, the T1056 (Input Capture) technique from MITRE ATT&CK is relevant to this rule."\\n    }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56862: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is detecting outbound HTTP POST requests from the local network to the internet, which indicates the use of an application layer protocol (HTTP) for communication, likely by malware (GORAT)."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for a specific pattern (\\\'murica\\\') in the HTTP POST request body, which could indicate data exfiltration over the command and control channel established by the GORAT malware."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50104: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50104",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an attempt to perform an SMB negotiation attack using the Responder tool, which is a type of Adversary-in-the-Middle attack. column5: {5784: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "5784",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a keylogger malware that is attempting to exfiltrate logs containing URLs browsed by the victim, which aligns with the Input Capture technique where adversaries capture user input data such as keystrokes or browsing activity."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "5784", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule suggests that the keylogger malware is attempting to exfiltrate the captured browsing logs over an SMTP channel, which is a common command and control channel used by malware for data exfiltration."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}
